0":"1220","1099":"1099","1250":"1250","1272":"1272","before about 1250":"vóór circa 1250","1060":"1060","Cambridgeshire, England":"Cambridgeshire, England","England":"England","Kent, England":"Kent, England"},"en":{"1216–1272":"1216–1272","1059–1099":"1059–1099","1080–Male":"1080–Deceased","1220–Female":"1220–Deceased","1250–Male":"1250–Deceased","1045–Male":"1045–Deceased","1060–Female":"1060–Deceased","1080":"1080","1216":"1216","1259":"1259","1224":"1224","1059":"1059","1045":"1045","1220":"1220","1099":"1099","1250":"1250","1272":"1272","before about 1250":"before about 1250","1060":"1060","Cambridgeshire, England":"Cambridgeshire, England","England":"England","Kent, England":"Kent, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Osbyrne","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Osbern</i>, partly from late Old English <i>Ōsbern</i>, an Anglicized form of Old Norse <i>Ásbiǫrn</i> (from <i>áss</i> ‘god’ + <i>biǫrn</i> ‘bear’), but more usually from Norman use of the cognate ancient Germanic <i>Ōsbern</i>. <i>Osbern</i> was often treated as an alternative form of <i>Osbert</i>. For pet forms see   Hoskin   and   Opie  . The surname has also been established in Ireland (Waterford, Tipperary) since the mid 16th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Osbon","meanings":["English (Sussex): variant of   Osborne  ."]},{"name":"Osbourn","meanings":["English: variant of   Osborne  ."]},{"name":"Osbourne","meanings":["English: variant of   Osborne  ."]},{"name":"Oborne","meanings":["English:","habitational name from Oborne in Dorset. The placename derives from Old English <i>wōh</i> ‘twisted, crooked’ + <i>burna</i> ‘spring, stream’.","possibly from the Middle English personal name <i>Obern</i>, an Anglo-Norman French form of <i>Osbern</i> (see   Osborne  )."]},{"name":"Orsburn","meanings":["English: variant of   Osborne  ."]},{"name":"Osbun","meanings":["English: variant of   Osborne  ."]},{"name":"Hoskin","meanings":["English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Osekin</i> with prosthetic <i>H-</i>, a pet form of Anglo-Norman French names beginning with <i>Os-</i> (particularly <i>Osbert</i>, as well as <i>Osbern</i>, and <i>Osmund</i>) + the Flemish diminutive suffix <i>-kin</i>. All three personal names were current in medieval Cornwall or Devon; see   Osborne  ,   Osmond  , and   Opie   (a pet form of <i>Osbert</i>). Old English <i>Ōsbeorn</i>, <i>Ōsbeohrt</i>, and <i>Ōsmund</i> may also have contributed in a minor way to Middle English usage; Middle English   Oswald   is another possible source, but the name was very rare in the late 14th century. For the excrescent initial <i>H-</i>, compare   Herrick  ."]},{"name":"Osborn","meanings":["English: variant of   Osborne  ."]},{"name":"Orsborn","meanings":["English: variant of   Osborne  ."]},{"name":"Oborn","meanings":["English (Somerset): habitational name chiefly from Oborne in Dorset, or perhaps occasionally from Howbourne Farm in Hadlow Down, Sussex, Woburn in Bedfordshire, Woburn Park in Surrey, or Wooburn in Buckinghamshire. The placenames derive from Old English <i>wōh</i> ‘twisted, crooked’ + <i>burna</i> ‘spring, stream’, except Wooburn in Buckinghamshire, which is of uncertain etymology.","English (of Norman origin): perhaps from the Middle English personal name <i>Obern</i>, an Anglo-Norman French form of <i>Osbern</i> (see   Osborne  )."]}]},{"name":"Henry","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["A perennially popular given name, of Continental Germanic origin, from <i>haim</i> ‘home’ + <i>rīc</i> ‘power, ruler’. It was an Old French name, adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. It has been borne by eight kings of England. Not until the 17th century did the form <i>Henry</i> (as opposed to   Harry  ) become the standard vernacular form, mainly under the influence of the Latin form <i>Henricus</i> and French <i>Henri</i>."],"variants":[]},{"name":"French","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English:","ethnic name for someone from France, from Middle English <i>frensh</i>, <i>frenche</i> ‘French’ (Old English <i>frencisc</i>), or in some cases, perhaps a nickname for someone who adopted French airs.","variant of Anglo-Norman French   Frain  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Frain","meanings":["Biblical.  See  <b>Ephraim</b> ."]},{"name":"Ffrench","meanings":["English: variant of   French  , which preserves a post-medieval spelling convention for representing an initial capital. It is most common in Jamaica."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705188,"age":8,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705189,"age":43,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Henry French Osbyrne was born in 1216, his father, Sir Richard Fitz Osborne, was 171 and his mother, Nesta verch Gwynedd, was 156. He married Mrs Henry French Osbyrne before about 1250, in England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1272, in Cambridgeshire, England, at the age of 56."},"et":{"1216–1272":"1216–1272","1059–1099":"1059–1099","1080–Male":"1080–Surnud","1220–Female":"1220–Surnud","1250–Male":"1250–Surnud","1045–Male":"1045–Surnud","1060–Female":"1060–Surnud","1080":"1080","1216":"1216","1259":"1259","1224":"1224","1059":"1059","1045":"1045","1220":"1220","1099":"1099","1250":"1250","1272":"1272","before ab